Question 30: What is the purpose of the "chown" command in Linux?
Answer: To make a file or folder recognize a specific user with root privileges, you can use the "chown" command along with the appropriate options. Here's how:

sudo chown username:groupname filename


This command changes the ownership of the specified file to the specified user and group. Replace "username" with the desired username, "groupname" with the desired group name, and "filename" with the name of the file or folder you want to change ownership for.


